Final Project: Bank Customer Churn

2024-06-15

Introduction

While the mere acquisition of new customers remains a large aspect of conducting business, retaining current customers is an integral part of the success and longevity of a company. Oftentimes, its more expensive for companies to gain new clients, than maintaining high rates of retention for current customers. By prioritizing customer retention, companies are spending less money while developing stronger bonds with their current set of clientele, ultimately improving the status and reputation of the company. Knowing which variables most greatly correlate with customer churn is incredibly insightful information for companies, as now that theyve identified the facets of customer service and experience that are leading to a loss of customers, they can improve them.

This sentiment extends to the industry of banking; customers are key to the operation and maintaining their company is crucial. Banking is a lifelong endeavor; individuals utilize banks and bank accounts as young as the age of 13 years old and will likely require the service of a bank for the rest of their life. Additionally, when bank customers have had a good experience with the particular bank theyre using, they can influence their children and/or relatives to join the same bank, meaning the company has acquired new customers through the maintenance of current relationships. The decision to stay at a bank can be impacted by a plethora of different variables. The following project operates to discover the variables that impact bank customer churn most greatly, utilizing the Bank Customer Churn data set by Kaggle user Radheshyam Kollipara to create a binary classification model that predicts customer churn. Regarding this particular data set, well specifically look at the outcome variable, exited, as its binary values are indicative of whether or not a customer left the bank.

Well begin, by importing, exploring, and tidying our data set. From there, well utilize machine learning techniques to split our data and create and run models. Well pit our models against each other to determine which fits the data set best, and then proceed to analyze our best model.

Access the full data set here: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/radheshyamkollipara/bank-customer-churn?resource=download

Ive imported necessary libraries and the data set. Based on brief initial exploration of the data, there are 10000 observations and 18 variables. There are no missing values. The 18 variables stored in the data set are defined below.

RowNumber: corresponds to the record (row) number and has no effect on the output.
CustomerId: contains random values and has no effect on customer leaving the bank.
Surname: the surname of a customer has no impact on their decision to leave the bank.
CreditScore: can have an effect on customer churn, since a customer with a higher credit score is less likely to leave the bank.
Geography: a customers location can affect their decision to leave the bank.
Gender: its interesting to explore whether gender plays a role in a customer leaving the bank.
Age: this is certainly relevant, since older customers are less likely to leave their bank than younger ones.
Tenure: refers to the number of years that the customer has been a client of the bank. Normally, older clients are more loyal and less likely to leave a bank.
Balance: also a very good indicator of customer churn, as people with a higher balance in their accounts are less likely to leave the bank compared to those with lower balances.
NumOfProducts: refers to the number of products that a customer has purchased through the bank.
HasCrCard: denotes whether or not a customer has a credit card. This column is also relevant, since people with a credit card are less likely to leave the bank.
IsActiveMember: active customers are less likely to leave the bank.
EstimatedSalary: as with balance, people with lower salaries are more likely to leave the bank compared to those with higher salaries.
Exited: whether or not the customer left the bank.
Complain: customer has complaint or not.
Satisfaction Score: Score provided by the customer for their complaint resolution.
Card Type: type of card hold by the customer.
Points Earned: the points earned by the customer for using credit card.

In the initial search of the data set, I noticed that some of the variable names have spaces in them, and all the variables use capital letters. To mitigate any issues that can potentially arise from these naming conventions, Ill use clean_names() to tidy the names. Additionally, based on the description of the variables listed above, originating from the source of the data set, Ill be dropping the variables RowNumber, CustomerId, and Surname, as theyre listed as having no impact on customer churn.

ccr_raw %>% select(-RowNumber, -CustomerId, -Surname) %>%

Exploratory Data Analysis

To begin to evaluate the impact of our predictor variables on our outcome variable, exited, lets create a correlation matrix of the numeric variables.

Here, we can see that balance and age are slightly positively correlated with exited. This means that as balances go up, customers are more likely to exit. Similarly, as age increases, likelihood of exiting increases. Exited is slightly negatively correlated with is_active_member and num_of_products. Complain and exited are perfectly positively correlated with a score of 1. The same variables that are slightly positively and negatively correlated with exited are also correlated with complain, indicating collinearity. To handle the collinearity, Ill drop complain in my final tidying of the data set.

Not associated with exited are num_of_products and balance being slightly negatively correlated with each other, while is_active_member and age are slightly positively correlated with each other.

Here we can see that our data is moderately imbalanced with around 80% of customers not exiting and 20% exiting. As such, I will be upsampling the data during the recipe stage, as the imbalance in the data could result in a models bias towards predicting when customers do not exit. Additionally, this imbalance indicates that the best metric to determine the optimal model is ROC AUC. ROC AUC stands for Receiver Operating Characteristic Area Under Curve. It measures specificity versus sensitivity in binary classification, meaning it provides measurements for our rates of both true and false positives and negatives.

They are defined as the following:

  • True Positive: our model predicts a customer will exit the bank, and the customer does exit the bank
  • False Positive: our model predicts a customer will exit the bank, but the customer does not exit the bank
  • True Negative: our model predicts a customer will not exit the bank, and the customer does not exit the bank
  • False Negative: our model predicts a customer will not exit the bank, but the customer does exit the bank
    With that unit of measurement in mind, lets further explore exiteds correlation with balance and age through a combination of box and violin plots.
ccr_updated %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=reorder(exited, balance), y = balance)) +
  geom_violin(fill = "gray", color = "black") +
  geom_boxplot(width=0.02, fill = "white", color = "black") +
  labs(x = "Exited",

Taking a look at customers that do not exit the bank, theres a large influx of individuals with low balances as shown by the width of the violin plot. This may indicate that these are people just joining the bank, as new customers might not have funds in their accounts yet and are unlikely to leave if theyve just joined. This is reflected in the longer interquartile range of those that stay. This pattern, while much less drastic, is reflected in those that leave, perhaps indicating people are emptying their accounts before exiting the bank. However, customers that exit have a larger range of balances in general. The median balance of those that stay is less than those that leave.

The median balance of those that stay is slightly under $100,000, while those that exit is higher at around $115,000.

Run Models

Split, Stratify, & Create Recipe

Now that weve gained some more insight into both our outcome variable and its corresponding predictor variables, as well as their correlations, well move on to our modeling stage. First, well ensure reproducibility by setting a seed. Additionally, well split our data into training and testing sets. This will ensure that our model is not evaluated on the data it was fit on, which would skew the accuracy of our model. We set the proportion of our split to .7, which places 6999 observations in our training set and 3001 in our testing set. We stratify the split on our outcome variable, exited, ensuring an approximately equal proportion among those that exit and do not exit in our training and testing sets. Well then utilize the technique of K-fold cross validation, which allows us to tune hyperparameters for different values and generalize our results by testing the models on multiple subsets of our data. We create the k-fold on our training data set, setting the folds to 5.

set.seed(614)
ccr_split <- initial_split(ccr, strata=exited, prop=.7)
ccr_split
## <Training/Testing/Total>
## <6999/3001/10000>
ccr_train <- training(ccr_split)
ccr_test <- testing(ccr_split)

ccr_folds <- vfold_cv(ccr_train, v=5, strata=exited)

Next, we create our recipe. I specify the outcome variable as exited and dummy code my nominal predictors, gender, geography, and card_type. Dummy coding nominal predictors involves turning my character variables into binary values, where each original value the variable could take on because either true or false. For example, the values of geography beyond the inital value thats stored get their own column. France is the first value stored in geography, so now that its been dummy-coded, we have new columns called geography_Germany and geography_Spain that take on binary values. A customer from Spain would have the values of geography at 0, geography_Germany at 0, and geography_Spain at 1. Alternatively, a customer from France would have the values of geography at 1, geography_Germany at 0, and geography_Spain at 0. I also center and scale my numeric data in step_normalize(), providing a standardized scale of measurement. Additionally, I will be upsampling my outcome variable to account for the imbalance of data. The upsampling at an over_ratio of 0.5 ensures that my minority data, customers that actually do exit, is scaled up to 50% of the majority data, customers that do exit. This particular ratio accounts for the imbalance without increasing the potential of overfitting. After setting up the recipe, I utilize the prep() and bake() functions to ensure that the recipe is running without errors.

ccr_recipe <- recipe(exited ~., data=ccr_train) %>%
  step_normalize(all_numeric()) %>%
  step_dummy(all_nominal_predictors(), one_hot = TRUE) %>%
  step_upsample(exited, over_ratio = 0.5)

prep(ccr_recipe) %>%
  bake(new_data = ccr_train) %>%
  head() %>% 
  kable() %>% 
  kable_styling(full_width = F) %>% 
  scroll_box(width = "100%", height = "200px")

Constructing & Fitting Models

Elastic Net Regression:

Our first model to be created is an Elastic Net Logistic Regression model. Elastic net regression is suitable for this model when utilized in combination with tuning, as it uses both lasso and ridge regression to find a balance between both that optimizes the model based on hyperparameters. I begin by tuning mixture, \(\alpha\), and penalty, \(\lambda\), so the model finds its own balance between lasso and ridge regularization. I create the workflow and form a grid with ten levels. I then tune and plot the models performance based on our desired metric, ROC AUC.

# Construct Model
ccr_en <- logistic_reg(mixture = tune(),
                           penalty = tune()) %>%
  set_mode('classification') %>%
  set_engine('glmnet')

# Workflow
ccr_en_wf <- workflow() %>%
  add_model(ccr_en) %>%
  add_recipe(ccr_recipe)

# Create Grid
ccr_en_grid <- grid_regular(penalty(range = c(0, 1),
                                     trans = identity_trans()),
                        mixture(range = c(0, 1)),
                             levels = 10)
# Tune Grid
ccr_en_tune <- tune_grid(
  object = ccr_en_wf, 
  resamples = ccr_folds, 
  grid = ccr_en_grid
)

autoplot(ccr_en_tune, metric = 'roc_auc') + theme_minimal()


The plot indicates that models with lower penalty values have higher ROC AUC scores, which is better. Additionally, it seems like mixture values below 0.5 score better.

KKNN:

The next model I selected was K-nearest neighbors, as neighbors can be tuned and used in a classification model. I followed the same steps as above, setting my range for neighbors to be between 1 and 10, as providing too many neighbors can result in overfitting. The model has 10 levels.

# Construct Model
ccr_kknn <- nearest_neighbor(neighbors=tune()) %>%
  set_mode("classification") %>%
  set_engine("kknn")

# Workflow
ccr_kknn_wf <- workflow() %>%
  add_model(ccr_kknn) %>%
  add_recipe(ccr_recipe)

# Create Grid
ccr_kknn_grid <- grid_regular(levels=10,
                              neighbors(range = c(1, 10)))

# Tune Grid
ccr_kknn_tune <- tune_grid(
  object = ccr_kknn_wf, 
  resamples = ccr_folds, 
  grid = ccr_kknn_grid
  )

autoplot(ccr_kknn_tune, metric='roc_auc') + theme_minimal()


The plot illustrates that the greater the number of neighbors, the higher the ROC AUC score. We might be tempted to increase our range of neighbors to larger than 10, however, increasing the number of neighbors can also increase bias, so Ill leave it as is.

Logistic Regression

Next, I chose a simple logistic regression in order to include a model with a minor computational time. This model has no hyperparameters to be tuned, so resampling occurs on the folds.

ccr_logreg <- logistic_reg() %>%
  set_engine('glm') %>%
  set_mode('classification')

ccr_logreg_wf <- workflow() %>%
  add_model(ccr_logreg) %>%
  add_recipe(ccr_recipe)

ccr_logreg_grid <- grid_regular(levels=10,
                         mixture(range=c(0,1)),
                         penalty())

ccr_logreg_tune <- tune_grid(
  object = ccr_logreg_wf, 
  resamples = ccr_folds, 
  grid = ccr_logreg_grid,
  control = control_grid(verbose = TRUE)
)

For uniformity of naming conventions, the last step has been assigned the name tune despite there being no hyperparameters to be tuned.

Random Forest:

The last model well be creating and evaluating is a Random Forest model. These models are good at avoiding overfitting, so given the upsampling in the recipe, random forest is a good model to create. The hyperparameters mtry and min_n are tuned. Mtry represents the number of random predictors randomly sampled. Min_n represents the minimum number of data points per node. Ive set trees to 500 to limit running time. Ive set the range of mtry to between 1 and 13, encompassing the range of predictor variables. Our minimum number of nodes per group is between 2 and 10. There are 5 levels.

ccr_rf <- rand_forest(mtry = tune(),
                      min_n = tune(),
                      trees = 500) %>%
  set_mode("classification") %>%
  set_engine("ranger", importance = "impurity")

# Workflow
ccr_rf_wf <- workflow() %>%
  add_model(ccr_rf) %>%
  add_recipe(ccr_recipe)

# Create Grid
ccr_rf_grid <- grid_regular(mtry(range = c(1, 13)), 
                            min_n(range = c(2, 10)),
                            levels = 5)

# Tune Grid
ccr_rf_tune <- tune_grid(
  ccr_rf_wf, 
  resamples = ccr_folds, 
  grid = ccr_rf_grid
)

autoplot(ccr_rf_tune, metric = 'roc_auc') + theme_minimal()


As the number of randomly selected predictors increases, so does the ROC AUC score up until around 7 predictors where the scores begin to taper off.

Optimal Model

Lets load our optimal model, finalize its workflow, and analyze the variable importance plot on our training set.

final_ccr_rf <- select_best(ccr_rf_tune, metric = 'roc_auc')

optimal_model <- finalize_workflow(ccr_rf_wf, final_ccr_rf)
optimal_model <- fit(optimal_model, ccr_train)

optimal_model %>% extract_fit_parsnip() %>% 
  vip() +
  theme_minimal()


The variable importance plot shows us which variables had the greatest impact on our outcome variable. Here we see that age has the most importance, with balance in second meaning that age and balance are the variables with the largest impact on the result of exited. We anticipated this result; in our correlation matrix from exploratory data analysis, these variables had a positive correlation with exited.
Finally, lets fit this model to our testing set.

optimal_test <- augment(optimal_model, ccr_test) %>% 
  select(exited, starts_with(".pred"))

roc_auc(optimal_test, truth = exited, .pred_0)
## # A tibble: 1  3
##   .metric .estimator .estimate
##   <chr>   <chr>          <dbl>
## 1 roc_auc binary         0.858
roc_curve(optimal_test, truth = exited, .pred_0) %>% 
  autoplot()

conf_mat(optimal_test, truth = exited, .pred_class) %>% 
  autoplot(type = "heatmap")


The ROC AUC score for the model on the test set is 0.8531, only a 0.0003 difference between our training set. The ROC AUC curve measures specificity versus sensitivity. Specificity represents our false positive rate, which is the rate in which we say a customer exited the bank when they have not. Sensitivity represents our true positive rate, which is the rate in which we say a customer has exited when they have actually exited. Based on our ROC AUC curve versus the straight baseline, our model performs significantly better than random guesses. Ideally, the curve mimics the shape of an upside down L, as the greater the space under the ROC curve indicates a better model performance, but the curve of our model is still good. Taking a look at our confusion matrix, we can evaluate the rates of true and false positives and negatives in greater detail. The left diagonal of boxes represents predictions that are true, while the right diagonal of boxes represents predictions that were not true.
Based on the values in the confusion matrix, were able to extract the following statistics:

  • 84.81% of customers (\(\frac{2545}{3001}\)) were classified correctly in regard to the outcome variable, exited
  • Sensitivity (true positive) rate is 64.72% (\(\frac{343}{530}\))
  • Specificity (true negative) rate is 89.11% (\(\frac{2202}{2471}\))

These statistics, along with the accompanying visuals, indicate that our model performs well overall, but performs better at predicting those that do not exit over those that do.

Conclusion

In conclusion, this project utilized the Bank Customer Churn data set from online data source, Kaggle, to predict whether or not a customer exited the bank or not and determine which factors majorly correlate with this decision. We discovered that the variables age, balance, point_earned, and estimated_salary are the variables that have the most impact on whether or not a customer exits the bank. In order to reach our conclusion, we created binary classification models using the modeling techniques of Elastic Net Regression, K-nearest Neighbors, Random Forest, and Logistic Regression. Our bank customer churn data set operated most effectively at predicting customer churn in the Random Forest Preprocessor01_Model08 with mtry = 7, min_n = 4, and trees set to 500. In hindsight, I wouldve liked to be able to tune the value of trees in my Random Forest model to a range between 500 and 1000 to see if we could make any improvements in the ROC AUC score. Unfortunately, my laptop is old and the computation of trees in that range was resulting in my software crashing. Ultimately, however, the model was able to strike a balance between sensitivity and specificity to obtain a ROC AUC score of about 0.85 on both the training and testing set.

Our next best model was Elastic Net, which similarly to the basic Logistic Regression, was able to receive a high ROC AUC score. These two models demonstrate the benefits of tuning, as the Elastic Net model performed slightly better than the straight Logistic Regression because of the ability to influence the values of penalty and mixture. Lastly, the K-nearest neighbors model performed significantly worse, as KKNN models have difficulty handling imbalanced data, though the score improved with the continued addition of neighbors. Looking to next steps, the imbalanced data of my outcome variable definitely had an impact on model performance. Moving forward, I would like to test out different resampling techniques of the outcome variable during the recipe building stage to observe the impact on performance. Overall, we were able to effectively create a machine learning binary classification model that predicts bank customer churn. In the real world, in combination with the discovery of highly correlated variables with exited, a bank would be bolstered by the new information discovered in this project to improve aspects of the banks customer service to improve customer retention.
